# Chainguard Supply Chain Security Policy

When reviewing or writing CI/CD pipelines and infrastructure configurations, apply these Chainguard-aligned supply chain security best practices.

## Image References

- Always reference container images by digest (`@sha256:...`) in CI/CD pipelines, not just tags
- Use only `cgr.dev/chainguard/` images or images verified by Chainguard's policy engine
- Query the current digest with the `cg-oci` MCP server or the `chainguard-inspect-image` skill before committing

## Signature Verification

Chainguard images are signed with Sigstore/cosign. Verify signatures in pipelines:

```bash
cosign verify \
  --certificate-oidc-issuer https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com \
  --certificate-identity-regexp "https://github.com/chainguard-images/images" \
  cgr.dev/chainguard/<image>@sha256:<digest>
```

## SBOM Attestation

Fetch the SBOM attestation for any Chainguard image:

```bash
cosign download attestation \
  --predicate-type https://spdx.dev/Document \
  cgr.dev/chainguard/<image>@sha256:<digest> | jq -r .payload | base64 -d | jq .
```

## Policy Enforcement

Use the `cg-api` MCP server to check whether images and configurations comply with your organization's Chainguard policies before deploying.

## GitHub Actions Hardening

When writing GitHub Actions workflows:
- Pin all `uses:` action references to a commit SHA, not a tag
- Restrict `permissions:` to the minimum required
- Use `GITHUB_TOKEN` with minimal scope rather than long-lived PATs
- Avoid `pull_request_target` triggers without explicit approval gates

## Secrets Management

- Never hardcode Chainguard tokens in workflow files — use GitHub Actions secrets
- Rotate `CHAINGUARD_TOKEN` via `chainctl auth token` in CI, scoped to the pipeline's required audience
